  "source": "InternalMed_Harrison_textbook_data.txt: 'Central diabetes insipidus (CDI) results from a deficiency of ADH secretion and is characterized by decreased urine concentration and increased urine volume. The syndrome in humans was first described in the 18th century and was shown to be associated with pituitary disease when patients with pituitary tumors presented with polyuria. CDI can be caused by a variety of diseases or injuries, including head trauma (vehicle accidents), neurosurgery, granulomas (especially those seen in Langerhans' cell histiocytosis), neoplasms, inflammation, autoimmune diseases, or vascular accidents. Head trauma and neurosurgery are the most common causes of CDI. Rare familial forms have also been reported in association with mutations in the gene encoding either vasopressin or vasopressin-neurophysin.'",
